  "prompt": "How does Augmented Reality Work?",
  "response": "Augmented Reality (AR) works through several key technologies and processes:\n\n1. Hardware Components\n- Camera for capturing real-world environment\n- Sensors (GPS, accelerometer, gyroscope)\n- Processing unit/computer\n- Display screen (smartphone, glasses, etc.)\n\n2. Key Technical Steps\n- Image recognition and tracking\n- Real-time environment mapping\n- 3D object rendering\n- Alignment and integration of digital content with physical world\n\n3. Core Technologies\n- Computer vision\n- Machine learning\n- Depth sensing\n- Object recognition algorithms\n\n4. Rendering Process\n- Detect real-world surfaces and environments\n- Calculate precise positioning\n- Overlay digital information/graphics\n- Adjust digital content in real-time based on user movement\n\n5. Common AR Types\n- Marker-based AR (uses specific visual markers)\n- Markerless AR (uses environmental features)\n- Projection-based AR\n- Superimposition AR\n\n6. Interaction Methods\n- Touch interfaces\n- Gesture recognition\n- Voice commands\n- Head/eye tracking\n\n7. Technical Requirements\n- High processing power\n- Low-latency rendering\n- Advanced graphics capabilities\n- Accurate sensor data\n\nAR fundamentally blends digital information seamlessly with the physical world through sophisticated real-time computational processes.",
